  <text>
    <body>
      <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.12393" xml:lang="en">
        <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
        <dateline>Simla in the Panjáb<note n="1" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <placeName>
Shimla</placeName> ist die Hauptstadt des indischen Bundesstaates Himachal Pradesh sowie des gleichnamigen Distrikts. Shimla gehörte früher zum Königreich <placeName>

Nepal</placeName>.</note>
          <lb/> 6 April 1882</dateline>
        <opener>Dear Sir</opener>
        <p> I have received your letter of the 4<hi
            rendition="#sup">th</hi> February and done my best to obtain for you the information as to <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.4423">Indo-Portuguese</ref> which you desire – I regret that I have failed in getting anything but the enclosed note from Mr Campbell<note
            n="2" place="foot"
            type="editorial">Sir <persName>

James Macnabb Campbell</persName>, KCIE (1846–1903).</note> , of the Bombay Secretariat, to my Colleague Mr. Gibbs<note
            n="3" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <persName>
James Gibbs</persName> (1825-1886), <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">I.C.S., Bar-at-Law</hi>.</note>. It strikes me that, next to Dr Gerson da Cunha<note n="4"
            place="foot" type="editorial">
            <persName
              ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1355">José Gerson da Cunha</persName> (1844-1900), Arzt in <placeName
              ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.348">Goa</placeName>, Indologe, Historiker, Linguist und Numismatiker; vgl. <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/context:hsa.letters.1355?locale=de">HSA 02225-02227</ref>.</note>, the best person to apply to, would be Dr Burnell<note
            n="5" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <persName
              ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1237">Arthur Burnell</persName> (1840-1882), britischer Sanskritist; vgl. <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/context:hsa.letters.1237">HSA 01466-01468</ref>.</note>, the distinguished Sanskritist, who is now in Europe. He has, I know, paid some attention do <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.844">Portuguese</ref> as well to Konkaní<note n="6"
            place="foot" type="editorial">
            <ref
              target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.3541">Konkani</ref> ist eine indoarische Sprache, die an der Westküste <placeName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.5898">Indiens</placeName>, insbesondere in Goa, gesprochen wird.</note> - G. da Cunhas pamphlet on which I send you by <pb
            facs="#IMG.2" n="2"/> bookpost as the Portuguese loan-words in that dialect may be interesting to you. </p>
        <p>I trust that, in spite of Prof. <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.3065">Zimmer</persName>’s brutal rudeness to Prof. <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.3018">
Windisch</persName>
          <note n="7" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.5224">Heinrich Zimmer, <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Keltische Studien</hi>. Erstes Heft: Irische Texte. Mit Wörterbuch von E. Windisch, Berlin: Weidmann’sche Buchhandlung, 1881.</ref>
            </bibl>

          </note>, you will pursue your Irish studies &amp;amp;, from time to time, publish the results. The harvest is great, but the labourers are few. I have sent you through Windisch a copy of my edition oft the <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Togail Troi</hi>
          <note n="8" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.10204">Whitley Stokes, <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Togail Troi: transcribed from the facsimile of the Book of Leinster and translation, with glossarial index of the rarer words</hi> =(The destruction of Troy), Calcutta: Leinster, 1881.</ref>
            </bibl>
          </note> which though full of faults, will, I trust, be of some little use to students of Middle- Irish. </p>
        <p> I leave this country for <pb facs="#IMG.3" n="3"/>
          <placeName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.6083">England</placeName> on the 28<hi
            rendition="#sup">th</hi> of this month. From 20<hi rendition="#sup">th</hi> to 31<hi
            rendition="#sup">st</hi> of May my address will be “5 Merrion Square North-Dublin.” After 31<hi rendition="#sup">st</hi> May it will be “9 Crick Road, Oxford” – </p>
        <closer>
          <salute>Yours sincerely </salute>
          <signed>
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2788">Whitley Stokes.</persName>
          </signed>
        </closer>
      </div>
